                        <h1>Hailan Yu, Age 13, "Chinatown Is My Home"</h1>
                        <div class="en">
                            <audio src="/audio/en/Hailan-Yu.mp3" controls>
                                Recording of Hailan Yu Story
                            </audio>
                            <p>Chinatown. Whenever I hear it, I think of home, Chinatown has always been my home. Ever since the day I was born, my first home was in Chinatown. For my entire 13 years of life, I have lived here with my family. Although I have moved once or twice, I still stayed in the same neighborhood. All my memories were built here. The vibe I get every day is just amazing. We know everyone really well.</p>

                            <p>When I was younger, I remember going to my cousins’ house every single day. It was just a block from my house. I remember how some of my cousins lived under the same roof as me too. It brought us closer together. I remember riding my bike with other kids on my block. It was one of those memories that will last forever. There was a time where I fell off my bike, and all the kids surrounded me. That was the feeling of affection. The fact that we were not related by blood, but they still helped me, it felt like family. I will always remember the warmth Chinatown gives me each and every day.</p>

                            <p>I remember the times that we use to go out after dinner and see all the kids on my block playing. We would all go to the park nearby. We played there for at least four hours a day. And in the summers, we were there all day long. It was one of the best things about summer. In the winter, we would build snowmen, makes snow angels, and drink hot chocolate together. My neighbors were one of the benefits of living in Chinatown. We always had fun together.</p>

                            <p>Another memory I have is that after school sometimes, my friends and I would go to somewhere in Chinatown to eat or drink something and either do homework or just talk. It was really fun and things like that made Chinatown a great place. It is where parents feel assured when their kids are here. It is a place where people of all ages have fun. That makes me want to grow old here.</p>

                            <p>I go to school in Chinatown too, which means I’m in Chinatown 24/7. Every day when I walk to school, I see a lot of kids going to school too. There are more than 3 schools in Chinatown and that means that there are many kids. It’s such an amazing atmosphere filled with the new generation. Chinatown has people all ages. We always make each feel welcome here. All the loved ones are surrounding me in this wonderful place I call home is the best thing ever.</p>

                            <p>In Chinatown, there’s basically everything. There are many great restaurants, beautiful sights, and a huge community. We have many great restaurants and shops, a library, many iconic attractions, schools, churches, and many homes. There are around 1,500 people living in Chinatown. There is always groups of tourist because Chinatown is truly an amazing place to visit.</p>

                            <p>My parents actually own a business in Chinatown. Knowing that there are other places that I can go to except my home, makes Chinatown feels safer. My parents basically know everyone in Chinatown. It really makes a difference when everyone is known here. Everyone who has lived in Chinatown has basically been here their whole lives. Everyone has different experiences and stories and that’s what makes Chinatown so great. Everyone has a different perspective of Chinatown, but they all lead to Chinatown being a home.</p>

                            <p>We have a lot of respect for our elders. Many of them are first-generation immigrants that set up this amazing place for us to live. I am a third generation American Chinese in the family. I thank my grandparents and others for making this place my home. Many people may not know the history of how Chinatown came to be, but many of our grandparents or even great-grandparents built the town the surrounds us. They wanted to make a community that would honor our culture, and that certainly happened. Chinatown has an authentic Chinese culture in it. Although over the years, some things have changed, the thing that will never change is how many of us call Chinatown our homes ,neighborhoods, people would go their own lives. But it’s different here. We care about each other and hope for the best for everyone.</p>
                            
                            <p>My experiences in Chinatown have been the best memories in my life. Chinatown is my home and forever will be.</p>
                        </div>
